Fun With Cmatrix in LinuxHave fun, Mr. Anderson! https://itsfoss.com/using-cmatrix/ 652e7d558ebe181c27aabcfe Terminal FunSreenath Wed, 18 Oct 2023 05:46:21 GMT <img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/install-cmatrix-in-linux.png" alt="Fun With Cmatrix in Linux"><p> Cmatrix is an entertaining command-line program for Linux and Unix systems. It gives a &#39;Matrix&#39;-style display, where a rain of green characters streams down the screen, just like in the iconic Matrix film series. </p><figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Cmatrix.gif" class="kg-image" alt="Fun With Cmatrix in Linux" loading="lazy" width="823" height="466" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/Cmatrix.gif 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Cmatrix.gif 823w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Cmatrix Command</span></figcaption></figure><p> But other than this green streams of characters, you can do several other things with this interesting command.</p><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-red"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 🚧</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> Cmatrix is a CPU intensive command. So use this with caution.</div></div><h2 id="install-cmatrix-in-ubuntu-and-other-linux-systems"> Install Cmatrix in Ubuntu and Other Linux systems</h2><p> Cmatrix is available in the official repositories of almost all major Linux distributions. In Ubuntu, you can install Cmatrix using the command:</p><pre> <code>sudo apt install cmatrix</code></pre><p> Fedora users should use:</p><pre> <code>sudo dnf install cmatrix</code></pre><p> Arch Linux user can use pacman:</p><pre> <code>sudo pacman -S cmatrix</code></pre><h2 id="basic-cmatrix-options"> Basic cmatrix options</h2><p> The cmatrix command alone provides several options, to change the appearance of the default output, that is the green character streams.</p><h3 id="bold-characters"> Bold characters</h3><p> You can either toggle the bold characters on using <code>-b</code> option, where you will find occasional bold characters,</p><pre> <code>cmatrix -b</code></pre> <figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/cmatrix-occasional-bold-characters.png" class="kg-image" alt="Fun With Cmatrix in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1170" height="607" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/cmatrix-occasional-bold-characters.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/cmatrix-occasional-bold-characters.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/cmatrix-occasional-bold-characters.png 1170w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Cmatrix with Occasional Bold Characters</span></figcaption></figure><p> or, turn all the characters to bold using:</p><pre> <code>cmatrix -B</code></pre> <figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/cmatrix-all-bold-characters.png" class="kg-image" alt="Fun With Cmatrix in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1170" height="607" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/cmatrix-all-bold-characters.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/cmatrix-all-bold-characters.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/cmatrix-all-bold-characters.png 1170w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">All Bold Characters</span></figcaption></figure><h3 id="asynchronous-scroll"> Asynchronous scroll</h3><p> The usual Cmatrix will create a display, where characters are falling down in a synchronous manner. In this mode, you can see a dynamic and visually engaging display, where the speed of the characters is varied.</p><p> To use Cmatrix in asynchronous scroll:</p><pre> <code>cmatrix -a</code></pre><h3 id="change-the-speed-of-characters"> Change the speed of characters</h3><p> Do you want to display the characters falling very fast, or very slow? You can do this in Cmatrix.</p><p> To make characters fall down fast, use:</p><pre> <code>cmatrix -u 2</code></pre> <figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Cmatrix-fast.gif" class="kg-image" alt="Fun With Cmatrix in Linux" loading="lazy" width="712" height="466" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/Cmatrix-fast.gif 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Cmatrix-fast.gif 712w"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Characters Moving Fast</span></figcaption></figure><p> Here, the default value of screen update delay is 4 and if you reduce it, the speed will be increased and vice versa. So, to run a slower cmatrix, use:</p><pre> <code>cmatrix -u 9</code></pre> <figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/cmatrix-slow.gif" class="kg-image" alt="Fun With Cmatrix in Linux" loading="lazy" width="712" height="466" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/cmatrix-slow.gif 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/cmatrix-slow.gif 712w"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Characters Moving Slow</span></figcaption></figure><h3 id="use-different-colors"> Use different Colors</h3><p> Go green! Or perhaps go purple?</p><p> You can run Cmatrix with a different color. For this, you can use the <code>-C</code> option.</p><pre> <code>cmatrix -C magenta</code></pre> <figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/cmatrix-magenta-color.png" class="kg-image" alt="Fun With Cmatrix in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1261" height="604" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/cmatrix-magenta-color.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/cmatrix-magenta-color.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/cmatrix-magenta-color.png 1261w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">The color is Magenta</span></figcaption></figure><p> The supported colors are <strong>green, red, blue, white, yellow, cyan, magenta and black</strong> .</p><h3 id="other-options"> Other Options</h3><table><thead><tr><th> Option</th><th> Function</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td> cmatrix -o</td><td> Old Style Scrolling</td></tr><tr><td> cmatrix -m</td><td> Lambda Mode: Every character becomes a lambda</td></tr><tr><td> cmatrix -s</td><td> Screensaver Mode: Exits on first keystroke</td></tr><tr><td> cmatrix -h</td><td> Help</td></tr></tbody></table><h2 id="cmatrix-keystrokes-during-execution"> Cmatrix keystrokes during execution</h2><p> Even if you don&#39;t provide any option in Cmatrix, you can provide some input later on during execution. Those are listed below.</p><h3 id="change-color"> Change Color</h3><p> Yes, you can change the color of characters while running. But you need to remember some keys and their corresponding color. What to do is, while running Cmatrix, press these keys and the color will change.</p><table><thead><tr><th> Color</th><th> Keystroke</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>红色的</td><td>!</td></tr><tr><td>绿色的</td><td>@</td></tr><tr><td>黄色的</td><td>#</td></tr><tr><td>蓝色的</td><td>$</td></tr><tr><td> Magenta</td><td> %</td></tr><tr><td> Cyan</td><td> ^</td></tr><tr><td> White</td><td> &amp;</td></tr><tr><td>黑色的</td><td>）</td></tr></tbody></table><h3 id="adjust-update-speed"> Adjust update speed</h3><p> While running, you can use the number keys from 0 through 9 to change the update speed.</p><p> There are other options also, which you can find from the man page of the command.</p><pre> <code>man cmatrix</code></pre><h2 id="bonus-cmatrix-with-lolcat"> Bonus: Cmatrix with lolcat</h2><div class="kg-card kg-callout-card kg-callout-card-red"><div class="kg-callout-emoji"> 🚧</div><div class="kg-callout-text"> Cmatrix itself is CPU intensive. So use the other commands with caution.</div></div><p> You can use Cmatrix, in combination with the lolcat command, to make it look more interesting. In Ubuntu, you can install lolcat using:</p><pre> <code>sudo apt install lolcat</code></pre><p> Now, just pipe Cmatrix to lolcat so that you will get a rainbow effect.</p><pre> <code>cmatrix | lolcat</code></pre> <figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Cmatrix-with-lolcat.png" class="kg-image" alt="Fun With Cmatrix in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1261" height="604" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/Cmatrix-with-lolcat.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/Cmatrix-with-lolcat.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/Cmatrix-with-lolcat.png 1261w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Cmatrix with Lolcat</span></figcaption></figure><p> Also, try all the above functions of Cmatrix, while piping into lolcat.</p><p> Or, you can use an inclined stripe for a rainbow effect, giving another type of experience.</p><pre> <code>cmatrix | lolcat -p 100</code></pre><p> Additionally, you can just invert the background and foreground colors so that your terminal will be filled with colors.</p><pre> <code>cmatrix | lolcat -i</code></pre> <figure class="kg-card kg-image-card kg-card-hascaption"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/cmatrix-with-inverse-colors.png" class="kg-image" alt="Fun With Cmatrix in Linux" loading="lazy" width="1261" height="604" srcset="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w600/2023/10/cmatrix-with-inverse-colors.png 600w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w1000/2023/10/cmatrix-with-inverse-colors.png 1000w, https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/10/cmatrix-with-inverse-colors.png 1261w" sizes="(min-width: 720px) 720px"><figcaption> <span style="white-space: pre-wrap;">Cmatrix with Lolcat Inverted Color Option</span></figcaption></figure><h2 id="more-fun-with-terminal"> More fun with terminal</h2><p> I know this is not the <a href="https://itsfoss.com/essential-ubuntu-commands/">most useful Linux command</a> but it&#39;s fun nonetheless and you can have some <a href="https://itsfoss.com/funny-linux-commands/">fun with your Linux system</a> sometime, right?</p><p> <a href="https://itsfoss.com/cowsay/">Cowsay</a> is another such command:</p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card"> <a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://itsfoss.com/cowsay/"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">Using Cowsay Linux Command Like a Pro</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-description">The cowsay is a fun little Linux command line utility that can be enjoyed in so many ways. Here are several examples.</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w256h256/2022/12/android-chrome-192x192.png" alt="Fun With Cmatrix in Linux"> <span class="kg-bookmark-author">It&#39;s FOSS</span> <span class="kg-bookmark-publisher">Sreenath</span></div></div> <div class="kg-bookmark-thumbnail"><img src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/2023/06/cowsay-linux-1.png" alt="Fun With Cmatrix in Linux"></div></a></figure><p> And even more here:</p><figure class="kg-card kg-bookmark-card"> <a class="kg-bookmark-container" href="https://itsfoss.com/funny-linux-commands/"><div class="kg-bookmark-content"><div class="kg-bookmark-title">13 Amusing Funny Linux Commands</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-description">So, you think Linux terminal is all work and no fun? These funny Linux commands will prove you wrong.</div> <div class="kg-bookmark-metadata"><img class="kg-bookmark-icon" src="https://itsfoss.com/content/images/size/w256h256/2022/12/android-chrome-192x192.png" alt="Fun With Cmatrix in Linux"> <span class="kg-bookmark-author">It&#39;s FOSS</span> <span class="kg-bookmark-publis